JSopX.OpenProjectX You're Here

JSopX.OpenProjectX.csproj:

The main project entry point, managing the overall application setup and coordination of other sub-projects.

Tech Stacks:

#JSopX #Bootstrap #Asp.NET Core #C-Sharp Android #Blazor MAUI Blazor Hybrid iOS Mac Catalyst macOS MAUI Mobile Tizen Windows Angular React Vue NodeJS HTML CSS JS TypeScript npm vite

JSopX.ClassLibrary

JSopX.ClassLibrary.csproj:

Contains shared business logic and utility functions used across multiple projects.

Tech Stacks:

#JSopX #Asp.NET Core #C-Sharp

JSopX.WebAPI

JSopX.WebAPI.csproj:

Provides RESTful API endpoints to support client-side applications and facilitate data exchange.

Tech Stacks:

#JSopX #Asp.NET Core #C-Sharp

JSopX.SharedResources

JSopX.SharedResources.csproj:

An older library containing shared assets such as images, styles, and scripts; still supported but gradually replaced by JSopX.RCLxAssets.

JSopX.RCLxProper

JSopX.RCLxProper.csproj:

A lightweight, production-optimized Razor Class Library containing only essential assets and resources for live environments.

JSopX.RCLxAssets

JSopX.RCLxAssets.csproj:

A comprehensive Razor Class Library with flexible support for all projects, containing static resources like images, CSS, JavaScript, and documentation.

JSopX.RCLxComponents

JSopX.RCLxComponents.csproj:

A Razor Class Library focusing on reusable Blazor and MAUI components, with plans for experimental support for Vue, React, and Angular components.

JSopX.AngularCore

JSopX.AngularCore:

The Angular & Asp.NET Core Web API Demo application which leverages the same assets, components & Web API all other projects in the JSopX™ Open Project EXperiences collection, and the Angular part of an Enterprise-Level, Multi-Platform, Multi-Stack Application.

JSopX.AngularCore.Server

JSopX.AngularCore.Server.csproj:

The server-side component of the Angular application, handling API interactions and server-side logic.

jsopx.angularcore.client

jsopx.angularcore.client.esproj:

The client-side Angular application, providing the user interface and client-side interactions.

JSopX.ReactCore

JSopX.ReactCore:

The React & Asp.NET Core Web API Demo application which leverages the same assets, components & Web API all other projects in the JSopX™ Open Project EXperiences collection, and the React part of an Enterprise-Level, Multi-Platform, Multi-Stack Application.

JSopX.ReactCore.Server

JSopX.ReactCore.Server.csproj:

The server-side component of the React application, handling API interactions and server-side logic.

jsopx.reactcore.client

jsopx.reactcore.client.esproj:

The client-side React application, providing the user interface and client-side interactions.

JSopX.VueCore

JSopX.VueCore:

The Vue & Asp.NET Core Web API Demo application which leverages the same assets, components & Web API all other projects in the JSopX™ Open Project EXperiences collection, and the Vue part of an Enterprise-Level, Multi-Platform, Multi-Stack Application.

JSopX.VueCore.Server

JSopX.VueCore.Server.csproj:

The server-side component of the Vue application, handling API interactions and server-side logic.

jsopx.vuecore.client

jsopx.vuecore.client.esproj:

The client-side Vue application, providing the user interface and client-side interactions.

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences)

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences) is my custom design pattern for enterprise-level, Multi-Platform, Multi-Stack development solutions.

Any project marked with the #JSopX hash tag, has all the necessary tools, assets, project references, and/or any other required JSopX™ based dependency injections.

Here is a code snippet:

                    
                         <div class="example-class">
                         <p>This is a sample HTML snippet.</p>
                         </div>

JSopX™ uses Bootstrap v 5.3

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences) uses Bootstrap v 5.3. All required Bootstrap needs, installations, and assets are already included in projects dependent on this release.

Any project marked with the #Bootstrap hash tag, have all the necessary tools, assets, project references, and/or any other required JSopX™ based dependency injections. No further action is required.

JSopX™ uses Asp.NET Core v 8.1

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences) uses Asp.NET Core v 8.1. All required Asp.NET Core needs, installations, and assets are already included in projects dependent on this release. However, this does not mean you have the version required installed on your machine.

Any project marked with the #Asp.NET Core hash tag, will require this version in order to run as expected.

Check Asp.NET Core version using Powershell

To check the Asp.NET Core version you have on your machine, open Powershell, and type or copy/paste: 

                    
                            dotnet --version

JSopX™ uses C# Sharp v 8.1

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences) uses C# Sharp v 8.1. All required C# Sharp needs, installations, and assets are already included in projects dependent on this release. However, this does not mean you have the version required installed on your machine.

Any project marked with the #C# Sharp hash tag, will require this version in order to run as expected.

Check C# Sharp version using Powershell

To check the C# Sharp version you have on your machine, open Powershell, and type or copy/paste: 

                    
                            dotnet --version

JSopX™ uses Blazor Server v 8.1

JSopX™ (Jason Silvestri Open Project EXperiences) uses Blazor Server v 8.1. All required Blazor Server needs, installations, and assets are already included in projects dependent on this release. However, this does not mean you have the version required installed on your machine.

Any project marked with the #Blazor Server hash tag, will require this version in order to run as expected.

Check Blazor Server version using Powershell

To check the Blazor Server version you have on your machine, open Powershell, and type or copy/paste: 

                    
                            dotnet --list-sdks
